\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The output of conventional oil and gas fields could have been described
 by Hubbert Curve 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hubbert1"

\end_inset

, a model that assumes a peek in production followed by a steady decline.
 In the US (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "oil_peak_fig"

\end_inset

) these maximum production output appeared to occur in the 1970s.
 Therefore as known techniques of hydrocarbons extraction were proving to
 be insufficient, efforts to find new ways of obtaining oil were made.
 The first pioneering papers on the topic of hydrofracturing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Crittendon,Geertsma,Harrison,Hubbert,Khristianovic,Nordgren,Perkins,SS"

\end_inset

 were published during that peek production time, as the industry realized
 the need to use new, unconventional methods of hydrocarbon recovery to
 meet the growing supply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename US_Crude_Oil_Production_versus_Hubbert_Curve.png
	scale 60

\end_inset


