\begin_layout Standard
In its broadest definition, 
\emph on
hydraulic fracturing refers to a problem of a fluid driven fracture propagating
 in a brittle medium
\emph default
.
 It is a naturally occurring process observable in formation of magma dykes
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rubin,Lister,Lister_Kerr"

\end_inset

 or subglacial drainage of water 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rice"

\end_inset

.
 The possible applications also go beyond petroleum industry: disposal of
 waste drill cuttings underground 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Moschovidis"

\end_inset

, geothermal reservoirs exploitation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pine"

\end_inset

 or coalbeded methane extraction.
 It is not the only reservoir stimulation method available, some other technique
s involve washing away remaining fossil fuels with specially prepared foam
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "simon"

\end_inset

.
 A typical hydrofracturing fracturing job, as shown on Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fracking_scheme"

\end_inset

, could be done in the following stages:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Drilling of a vertical well, or preparation of an existing one if stimulating
 depleted reservoir.
 The wells walls must be prepared to withstand massive pressures without
 unanticipated leak to the ground waters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Drilling of a long horizontal section that spans throughout target resource
 rich rock formation, which could be some gas rich shale as shown on Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "gas_picture"

\end_inset

.
 It is a fairly recent technique that requires proper horizontal drilling
 heads.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Preparation of initial fractures with directed explosive charges.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Pumping of fracturing fluid.
 This could go on for days, and requires substantial reserves of water,
 chemical additives, and powerful pumps
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Apparently to extract oil one must first burn some oil
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mixing in proppant.
 This hard solid additive spreads inside fractures and prevents them from
 closing, after pumping is stopped.
 Sand, or other granulate material such as ceramic grains can be used, provided
 it is hard enough to hold drained fracture walls opened.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
And finally moving on to production phase, capturing hydrocarbons that flow
 out of the created fractures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The process is indeed very sophisticated and expensive, but pays off.
 Due to its application, the Hubbert Curve has been beaten 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cavallo"

\end_inset

 and the popularized in the mass media forecast of fossil fuel depletion
 appears to be postponed for the next century.
 Indeed over the past decade natural gas production in the US alone increased
 by over 50% 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "usa_gas_production"

\end_inset

 due to the recent shale gas boom.
 This was achieved by widespread application of hydrofracturing.
 Shale gas deposits, as opposed to conventional sandstones, have natural
 gas trapped in pores of non permeable shale formations (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "gas_picture"

\end_inset

 again).
 Hydrofracturing, pumping fluid under extremely high pressures opens new
 fractures, and creates pathways for the natural gas to escape these pores
 in shale and flow all the way to the surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This work should cover only a single stage of the hydrofracturing process,
 the numerical modeling of fracture propagation due to fluid pumping.
 Although it is only a single stage of this large multiphysics problem,
 modeling fracture propagation is already a sufficient enough challenge
 on its own to produce interesting and novel research.
 The previous physical concepts: pressure, porosity and permeability of
 the reservoir will now be coupled with incompressible viscous fluid dynamics,
 fracture mechanics and complex non static geometries into a dynamic mathematica
l model.
 This will cover the evolution of short initial fractures located right
 at the drilled wellbore, to an underground system of multiple fractures,
 that could span over several kilometers.
 The engineering and geological challenges of choosing right drilling place,
 preparing a sufficient horizontal well at depths of up to a few kilometers,
 and maintaining later production will not be covered here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem of proppant mixing and transportation, that follows immediately
 after the stage of fracture propagation will not be mentioned here.
 Taking proppant into consideration would introduce even more physical propertie
s and processes, which would extend the overall complexity beyond manageable
 level.
 Even the oldest and relatively simple proppant model by Einstein 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Einstein"

\end_inset

, might not describe the actual physical process correctly 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kuzkin"

\end_inset

, but would make fluid viscosity dependent on proppant concentration, thus
 add yet another variable.
 Furthermore other thermal and chemical processes would need to be taken
 care of as these also affect fluid viscosity, therefore it is reasonable
 to exclude these and simply assume uniform constant viscosity of fracturing
 fluid.
\end_layout

